Hierarchy Experiment: Descriptive statistics

Bodo Winter (statistical analysis)

7/17/2019

Introduction

This is the statistical analysis of our hierarchy experiment, a replication-extension of Schuberts (2005) study which associates vertical positions with power. The present study includes the added dimension of gender.

This script performs descriptive statistics and plotting.

Preprocessing

Load stuff:

# Packages:

library(tidyverse)
library(gridExtra)

# Data:

power <- read_csv('data/hierarchy_experiment_cleaned.csv')

# ggplot2 theme:

source('timo_theme.R')

Demographics to report

Overall number of participants to report:

length(unique(power$Subj))
## [1] 62

Check gender composition:

# Create a table with subject identifiers by gender:

gender_tab <- table(power$Subj, power$SubjGender)

# Check 0 counts to get number of genders:

genders <- apply(gender_tab, 1, FUN = function(x) ifelse(x[1] == 0, 'male', 'female'))

# How many each?

table(genders)
## genders
## female   male 
##     51     11

Compute averages:

First, overall response times:

power %>% summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
                    SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##       M    SD
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  1790   707

Next by overall participant gender:

power %>% group_by(SubjGender) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   SubjGender     M    SD
##   <chr>      <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female      1809   722
## 2 male        1705   628

Next by overall hierarchy condition:

power %>% group_by(HierarchyCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   HierarchyCond     M    SD
##   <chr>         <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 BottomPower    1797   708
## 2 TopPower       1784   707

Slightly faster (~20ms) when bottom(!) is powerful.

Next by gender condition:

power %>% group_by(GenderCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   GenderCond     M    SD
##   <chr>      <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 FemaleTop   1784   698
## 2 MaleTop     1797   717

Slightly faster (~30ms) when the woman is on top.

Next by gender and hierarchy condition:

power %>% group_by(GenderCond, HierarchyCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   GenderCond [2]
##   GenderCond HierarchyCond     M    SD
##   <chr>      <chr>         <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 FemaleTop  BottomPower    1771   694
## 2 FemaleTop  TopPower       1797   701
## 3 MaleTop    BottomPower    1823   721
## 4 MaleTop    TopPower       1771   712

Looks like an interaction. When the woman is on top peple are SLOWER if the woman is also more powerful. When the man is on top, people are FASTER if the man is also more powerful. The slowest response times are obtained for when the man is on top but the more powerful position is female and at the bottom.

Another way to look at these results is to focus on the one where the bottom position is the more powerful one (HierarchyCond = BottomPower). In that case, people are faster when the man is the more powerful.

Another way to look at this, whether people find it overall easier/harder if male = powerful:

power %>% group_by(GenderPower) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   GenderPower         M    SD
##   <chr>           <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female=powerful  1810   711
## 2 male=powerful    1771   703

People are faster in the male = powerful condition.

Lets break this up by hierarchy condition (verticality):

power %>% group_by(GenderPower, HierarchyCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   GenderPower [2]
##   GenderPower     HierarchyCond     M    SD
##   <chr>           <chr>         <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female=powerful BottomPower    1823   721
## 2 female=powerful TopPower       1797   701
## 3 male=powerful   BottomPower    1771   694
## 4 male=powerful   TopPower       1771   712

Lets break this up by task:

power %>% group_by(Task) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   Task          M    SD
##   <chr>     <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 powerful   1628   634
## 2 powerless  1960   739

People find it MUCH easier to pick the powerful one, by almost 500ms.

Lets see whether the hierarchy condition interacts with Task:

power %>% group_by(Task, HierarchyCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   Task [2]
##   Task      HierarchyCond     M    SD
##   <chr>     <chr>         <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 powerful  BottomPower    1627   629
## 2 powerful  TopPower       1629   640
## 3 powerless BottomPower    1976   742
## 4 powerless TopPower       1945   737

When participants are picking the powerful one, they are faster with the bottom being at the powerful position. This goes against Schubert (2005). When participants are picking the powerless one, there is a slight effect in the predicted direction with the top = powerful being slightly faster.

Lets look at task and gender:

power %>% group_by(Task, GenderCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   Task [2]
##   Task      GenderCond     M    SD
##   <chr>     <chr>      <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 powerful  FemaleTop   1628   623
## 2 powerful  MaleTop     1628   646
## 3 powerless FemaleTop   1945   734
## 4 powerless MaleTop     1976   744

Lets look at the double match variable:

power %>% group_by(DoubleMatch) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))  
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   DoubleMatch              M    SD
##   <chr>                <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 male powerful on top  1771   712
## 2 no match              1797   706

Lets look at this as a function of task:

power %>% group_by(Task, DoubleMatch) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   Task [2]
##   Task      DoubleMatch              M    SD
##   <chr>     <chr>                <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 powerful  male powerful on top  1621   651
## 2 powerful  no match              1631   629
## 3 powerless male powerful on top  1930   739
## 4 powerless no match              1971   739

The effect goes into opposite directions based on task! If people have to select the powerless one, they are fast if the women are at the bottom. If they have to select the powerful one, they are SLOWER(!) if they pick the male on top.

Lets break this up by participant gender:

power %>% group_by(SubjGender, DoubleMatch) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   SubjGender [2]
##   SubjGender DoubleMatch              M    SD
##   <chr>      <chr>                <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female     male powerful on top  1801   724
## 2 female     no match              1812   721
## 3 male       male powerful on top  1637   639
## 4 male       no match              1729   623

Massive difference where the male participants are showing a 100 ms drop if the men is powerful and on top!

Are people overall faster when they have to pick the male response or when they have to pick the female response?

power %>% group_by(PickedGender) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   PickedGender     M    SD
##   <chr>        <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female        1810   711
## 2 male          1771   703

Overall faster selecting the male.

Does this differ by subject gender?

power %>% group_by(SubjGender, PickedGender) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
## # Groups:   SubjGender [2]
##   SubjGender PickedGender     M    SD
##   <chr>      <chr>        <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 female     female        1816   726
## 2 female     male          1802   719
## 3 male       female        1781   639
## 4 male       male          1632   610

The men are overall faster at picking the male response. The women have the same directional preference, but less pronounced.

power %>% group_by(SubjGender,

How does the hierarchy effect depend on subject gender?

By-item averages:

Look at how the gender effect differs by item:

item_gender <- power %>%
  group_by(PairName, GenderCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0))

item_gender$Facet <- rep(str_c('Group', 1:4),
                         each = 16)

p1 <- item_gender %>% 
  filter(Facet == 'Group1') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PairName,
             fill = GenderCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') + 
  coord_flip(ylim = c(1500, 2000)) + 
  theme_bham_stats +
  theme(legend.position = 'top')
p2 <- item_gender %>% 
  filter(Facet == 'Group2') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PairName,
             fill = GenderCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') + 
  coord_flip(ylim = c(1500, 2000)) + 
  theme_bham_stats +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
p3 <- item_gender %>% 
  filter(Facet == 'Group3') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PairName,
             fill = GenderCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') + 
  coord_flip(ylim = c(1500, 2000)) + 
  theme_bham_stats +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
p4 <- item_gender %>% 
  filter(Facet == 'Group4') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PairName,
             fill = GenderCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') + 
  coord_flip(ylim = c(1500, 2000)) + 
  theme_bham_stats +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow = 4, ncol = 1)

Visualizations

First, the effect of picking the male response:

power %>%
  group_by(SubjGender, PickedGender) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PickedGender, fill = PickedGender, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  facet_wrap(~SubjGender) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(1600, 1900)) + 
  theme_bham_stats

Second, the hierarchy effect:

power %>%
  group_by(SubjGender, HierarchyCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = HierarchyCond, fill = HierarchyCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  facet_wrap(~SubjGender) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(1600, 1900)) + 
  theme_bham_stats

Third, the gender condition effect:

power %>%
  group_by(SubjGender, GenderCond) %>% 
  summarize(M = round(mean(RT), 0),
            SD = round(sd(RT), 0)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = GenderCond, fill = GenderCond, y = M)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  facet_wrap(~SubjGender) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(1600, 1900)) + 
  theme_bham_stats
